        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "So I looked a bit into the vanilla build scripts:\r\n\r\n1. `make` builds a `luajit` binary under `src/`\r\n2. `make install` copies that to `luajit-2.1.<hash>`\r\n3. as you observed, `<hash>` is empty if the `.git` directory is missing\r\n4. even with a `.git` directory, the `make install` step fails for me with \r\n```\r\n==== Installing LuaJIT 2.1.1692616192 to . ====\r\nmkdir -p ./bin ./lib ./include/luajit-2.1 ./share/man/man1 ./lib/pkgconfig ./share/luajit-2.1/jit ./share/lua/5.1 ./lib/lua/5.1\r\ncd src && install -m 0755 luajit ./bin/luajit-2.1.1692616192\r\ninstall: ./bin/luajit-2.1.1692616192: No such file or directory\r\nmake: *** [install] Error 71\r\n```\r\n\r\nSo it looks like the new \"rolling release\" model still has some rough spots and \r\n>  assuming the version numbers are monotonically increasing and not random nonsense.\r\n\r\nis unfortunately not true.\r\n\r\nThe most robust option (given the current upstream Makefile) would be to _not_ rely on `make install` and instead manually copy the files ourselves from the source tree instead -- if that is possible.",
